    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters today\u2019s slate prioritizing high-order batting positions and favorable SP xERAs to chase efficiency in a league where stolen bases remain the ultimate scarcity. **Vinnie Pasquantino** (72.92) is our strongest play, benefiting from a prime matchup against Civale and a 10% park boost, anchoring the 1B spot with elite projection. **Seiya Suzuki** (68.80) and **Corbin Carroll** (66.51) follow closely as our top outfield threats. **Suzuki** is positioned to feast on a favorable 5.19 xERA matchup, while **Carroll** remains our most volatile yet essential engine; despite the matchup against a high-hold-rate starter, his ability to capitalize on small windows of opportunity makes him a daily lock. **James Wood** (64.83) also draws high-leverage consideration, as his leadoff spot and favorable SP skill boost outweigh the concerns surrounding a high-hold opposing pitcher.\n\nThe bench decision for today proved difficult, with **Josh Naylor** (53.45) falling just shy of the active roster. While **Naylor** provided a solid floor, the optimizer favored the structural versatility of **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (54.27) and the park-adjusted upside of **Tyler Soderstrom** (53.15). We opted to bench **Jose Caballero** (41.61) primarily due to the severe xERA penalty posed by deGrom, which significantly suppressed his value in our 5x5 scoring model. We must keep a close watch on **Mickey Moniak** (57.59); while his score is boosted by a strong platoon edge and top-of-the-order status, he is facing a challenging arm in Burns, presenting the highest risk of underperforming his raw projection today. **Dalton Rushing** (58.51) rounds out the high-upside group, though we remain wary of the efficiency impact if the lower-tier hitters fail to turn the lineup over.",
